article.description: Nicole Powell forced overtime with a 3-pointer and sank a key jumper in the final minute as Sacramento edged host  Houston 73-69 in Game 1 of the West finals.
article.headline: Powell leads Monarchs to OT win at Houston
article.linkText: Powell leads Monarchs to OT win at Houston
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- The biggest shot of Nicole Powell's career has
the Sacramento Monarchs just one win away from their first trip to
the WNBA finals.

Powell forced overtime Thursday night with a desperation
3-pointer with four seconds left in regulation and the Monarchs
went on to defeat the Houston Comets 73-69.

The Monarchs scored the first six points in overtime and took
the lead for good when DeMya Walker made a layup with 4.2 seconds
to go.

"That, for sure, was the biggest shot of my professional
career," Powell said. "My role is to get open and hit the outside
shots. As a team we had to be ready for this and everybody just fed
off each other. That has been our story all year."

Walker, who finished with 11 points, played for the first time
since Aug. 18 while nursing a sprained right knee. She didn't
start, but made four of her nine shots and added six rebounds.

Yolanda Griffith scored 14 points and Kara Lawson added 12 for
the Monarchs.

In three of the past four years, Sacramento has been eliminated
from the West Finals by Los Angeles twice (2001 and 2003) and
Seattle (2004) but can earn a trip to the finals with a win over
Houston on Saturday or, if necessary, Sunday.

Griffith played a team-high tying 35 minutes and made six of her
15 shots while leading the Monarchs with eight rebounds.

"Even though we won, our backs are still against the wall,"
Griffith said. "Houston has four great players and we know they're
not going to quit. We know that."

Sheryl Swoopes scored 14 of her game-high 19 points in the
second half for Houston. Tina Thompson added 18 points and Michelle
Snow had 14.

The Comets, who committed a team playoff record 20 turnovers,
used a 6-0 run to turn a three-point deficit into a three-point
lead before Powell's heroics.

Thompson and Canty pulled down seven rebounds apiece for
Houston, which enjoyed a 32-26 advantage on the boards.

"This is not something that we wanted," Swoopes said. "We dug
ourselves into a pretty big hole, but we came back. But we really
couldn't ever get into any kind of flow. I think we were more
concerned tonight with what they were going to do and that really
hurt us tonight."

Chelsea Newton hit a long 3-pointer with 1:21 left in the second
half to give the Monarchs a 60-57 lead, but Thompson made a pair of
free throws to get the Comets within a point with 56 seconds left.

Houston forced a turnover 16 seconds later, and Swoopes gave the
Comets a 61-60 lead by hitting a 13-footer with 27 seconds left.

There were 13 lead changes in the first half, but the Monarchs
shot well enough to take a 30-28 lead at the break.

"Give Nicole Powell credit for making a great shot," said
Comets head coach Van Chancellor. "I thought when we got up by
three points, we'd have a shot at them. I just could not get the
play I wanted to run at the end and that hurt us some too.

"They did a good job of taking us out of our offense."

Lawson started in place of injured guard Ticha Penicheiro, who
sprained her left ankle in practice on Tuesday.

Penicheiro is listed as day-to-day, but is not expected to play
in the series.

"She might want to play, but she doesn't have any wheels,"
John Whisenant said. "I hope she comes back and surprises me."
